_name\": \"2-(2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanamido)-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"histidyl-histidine\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H5N5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"9H-purin-6-amine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"adenine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H5N5/c6-5-4-3(8-1-7-4)9-2-10-5/h1-2H,(H2,6,7,8,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions; anoxic; H2-rich serpentinization setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to surface-bound formyl/formate species, released as formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal Fe-S catalyzed CO2 reduction is a well-supported source of reduced C1 feedstocks that can feed downstream surface synthesis networks relevant to histidine precursor generation (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; He et al., 2010).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type formation of glycolaldehyde from reduced C1 feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/elemental iron\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor hydrothermal or vent-associated FT-type synthesis under anoxic conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Successive reduction and C-C coupling of C1 units on magnetite/Fe0 surfaces gives small oxygenated aldehydes including glycolaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research identifies small sugar precursors such as glycolaldehyde as central feedstocks in cyanosulfidic and imidazole chemistry; hydrothermal FT-type reactions are used here as a geochemically plausible source linking vent carbon fixation to surface networks (Cody et al., 2000; Roldan et al., 2015). This step is partly connective/speculative because the report emphasizes glycolaldehyde availability rather than a single mandatory source.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photochemical generation and concentration of hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide mineral photoredox surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated evaporitic or volcanic surface setting; atmospheric discharge-derived nitrile chemistry concentrated in pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoredox and nitrile-forming atmospheric/surface chemistry generates HCN, which is trapped and concentrated in shallow pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies HCN as the primary carbon and nitrogen source in both cyanosulfidic and purine-linked networks and notes atmospheric discharge plus UV-driven surface chemistry as critical feedstock generators (Miller, 1953; Patel et al., 2015; Ferris & Orgel, 1966). Exact direct conversion from formate/ammonia is a network-bridging abstraction of documented HCN-generating prebiotic contexts.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamidine formation from HCN and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite with UV-active mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated aqueous pools; transient accumulation limited by hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN and NH3 undergo addition/rearrangement to amidine functionality under concentrated, mildly evaporative conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly identifies formamidine as the key nitrogen-rich reagent formed from HCN and NH3, but emphasizes that its hydrolytic instability is a major bottleneck; mineral concentration is included to address this gap plausibly (Shen et al., 1990; Or\u00f3 & Shen, 1969).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanamide formation from HCN-derived nitrile chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-photocatalytic mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed cyanosulfidic setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical nitrile transformations furnish cyanamide as a reactive condensed nitrile/amidine equivalent.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanamide is highlighted in the report as a versatile prebiotic reagent and direct precursor in 2-aminoimidazole synthesis. This step is included as a necessary network connection from the common HCN pool and is chemically consistent with prebiotic nitrile chemistry, though the exact route is less specifically detailed in the report (Sutherland, 2016; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose-derived conversion of glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde and erythrose\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals with clay concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pools; wet-dry concentration; borate stabilization of higher sugars\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol/formose chemistry homologates glycolaldehyde to triose and tetrose products, with borate selectively stabilizing useful sugar isomers including erythrose.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies erythrose as the key tetrose precursor in the Shen-Or\u00f3 route and glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde as central small sugars in systems chemistry; borate-stabilized formose chemistry is the standard prebiotic route connecting them (Benner et al., 2012; Ricardo et al., 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Shen-Or\u00f3 condensation of erythrose with formamidine to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration by clay and borate-stabilized sugar pools\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated aqueous environment; one-pot precursor mixture; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation of the tetrose with formamidine gives an aminoaldose/amino-ketose manifold followed by Amadori-type rearrangement and cyclization to the imidazole aldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the central literature-supported proximal histidine route: erythrose + formamidine yields imidazole-4-acetaldehyde via an Amadori-type rearrangement/cyclization under prebiotically plausible aqueous conditions (Shen, Or\u00f3, & Miller, 1987; Shen et al., 1990).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker conversion of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde to histidine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay concentration with phosphate-buffered aqueous medium\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"classical Strecker conditions in the same reaction mixture; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldehyde imination with ammonia followed by cyanide addition gives the alpha-aminonitrile precursor to histidine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research explicitly states that imidazole-4-acetaldehyde is converted to histidine through classical Strecker synthesis, first forming the alpha-aminonitrile and then hydrolyzing to the amino acid (Shen, Or\u00f3, & Miller, 1987; Miller, 1957).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of histidine aminonitrile to histidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prolonged aqueous hydrolysis during geothermal cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis proceeds through amide to carboxylate, yielding the amino acid histidine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This final hydrolysis step is part of the documented Shen-Or\u00f3 one-pot histidine synthesis and accounts for the reported overall ~3.5% yield from erythrose (Shen, Or\u00f3, & Miller, 1987; Shen et al., 1990).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphate-catalyzed cyanosulfidic synthesis of 2-aminoimidazole from glycolaldehyde and cyanamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"inorganic phosphate\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"acidic to near-neutral pH ~5-7; high ammonium; cyanosulfidic conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation and cyclization of glycolaldehyde with cyanamide under phosphate buffering forms the aminoimidazole heterocycle.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies this as a significant modern breakthrough: glycolaldehyde + cyanamide + phosphate/ammonium under mildly acidic conditions yields 2-aminoimidazole in good selectivity, demonstrating ready prebiotic access to a histidine-side-chain analog (Sutherland and coworkers; Xu et al., 2017; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization to aminoimidazole carboxamide and adenine pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted concentration and photochemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"HCN-rich evaporitic or frozen-concentrating pools; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN oligomerization and partial hydrolysis generate purine-related imidazole carboxamide intermediates, branching to adenine and AIC-like compounds.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report states that AIC and related purine intermediates can be synthesized abiotically from HCN and NH3 and emphasizes molecular convergence between histidine and purine chemistry; adenine synthesis from HCN is a classic precedent (Or\u00f3, 1961; Ferris et al., 1978).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Prebiotic glycosylation/phosphorylation of AIC to AICAR\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mineral interface or drying-rehydration cycles favoring ribosylation and phosphorylation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise ribosylation of the aminoimidazole carboxamide base followed by phosphorylation yields the nucleotide-like branch-point AICAR.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report highlights AICAR as the shared branch point between purine and histidine biosynthesis in extant biology and notes abiotic simulations yielding AIC/AICAR-related compounds. The exact abiotic assembly sequence remains less well constrained, so this connecting step is retained as a necessary but partially speculative bridge (White, 1976; Orgel, 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Salvage convergence of aminoimidazole and AIC/AICAR pool to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"geothermal cycling and redox/hydrolytic turnover in mixed prebiotic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolysis, deamination, decarboxamide loss, and side-chain editing within a shared imidazole heterocycle pool converge on the aldehyde-bearing imidazole scaffold.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report strongly argues for molecular convergence between histidine and purine chemistry through shared imidazole intermediates, but does not provide a single experimentally established abiotic conversion from 2-aminoimidazole or AIC/AICAR to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde. This node-connecting salvage reaction is therefore explicitly speculative, added only to integrate the literature-supported imidazole pools into a complete network (Shen et al., 1990; Patel et al., 2015; White, 1976).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanamide-mediated condensation of histidine to histidyl-histidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"cyanamide\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated pools or wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanamide activates carboxylate function, enabling peptide bond formation between two histidine monomers.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report states that histidyl-histidine dipeptides have been synthesized in notable yield using cyanamide and that such peptides show catalytic behavior, supporting a downstream biochemical role for prebiotically formed histidine (Rode, 1999; the deep research summary on cyanamide-mediated His-His formation).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical Shen-Or\u00f3 route from erythrose\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface tetrose erythrose condenses with formamidine to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde, then undergoes Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface Shen-Or\u00f3 route via vent-derived glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduction produces glycolaldehyde, which is converted on the surface into erythrose and then follows the Shen-Or\u00f3 sequence to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-fed Shen-Or\u00f3 one-pot route\",\n      \"description\": \"A common HCN pool forms formamidine and also supplies the Strecker cyanide for direct one-pot conversion of erythrose-derived imidazole aldehyde to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic aminoimidazole convergence to histidine\",\n      \"description\": \"Glycolaldehyde and cyanamide produce 2-aminoimidazole, which is connected through the shared imidazole salvage pool to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde and then to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Purine-linked AIC route to histidine\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN oligomerization yields AIC and related purine intermediates that converge through the imidazole salvage pool to the proximal histidine precursor.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Purine-linked AICAR route to histidine\",\n      \"description\": \"AIC is ribosylated/phosphorylated to AICAR, reflecting biological branch-point convergence, then salvaged back into the imidazole aldehyde pool en route to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual-imidazole convergence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Both 2-aminoimidazole and AIC/AICAR are generated independently and jointly feed the shared imidazole salvage step leading to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-formate assisted HCN-to-histidine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Vent-derived formate supports a surface HCN pool, which then feeds both formamidine production and Strecker chemistry for histidine synthesis through the canonical aldehyde intermediate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Erythrose-first route with later HCN capture\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface sugar chemistry first accumulates erythrose from glycolaldehyde; later arrival of formamidine and HCN closes the ring and completes Strecker conversion to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Histidine-to-functional-peptide extension\",\n      \"description\": \"After histidine formation through the Shen-Or\u00f3 route, cyanamide-mediated peptide condensation yields histidyl-histidine, demonstrating biochemical utilization of the target in prebiotic networks.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_019\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Histidine", "overall_strategy": "The network centers on literature-supported convergence onto imidazole-bearing intermediates from three interconnected prebiotic domains. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced C1/C2 feedstocks (formate, glycolaldehyde) and nitrogen/carbon precursors (HCN-linked inputs) through Fe-S and magnetite catalysis. Surface chemistry then performs the key heterocycle-generating steps documented for histidine-related chemistry: (i) Shen-Or\u00f3 erythrose + formamidine condensation to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde followed by Strecker conversion to histidine, (ii) cyanosulfidic production of 2-aminoimidazole from glycolaldehyde + cyanamide in phosphate-buffered settings, and (iii) HCN oligomerization to purine-linked aminoimidazole carboxamide intermediates. Biochemical/prebiotic stages connect these imidazole hubs through glycosylation, phosphorylation, hydrolysis, transamination-like salvage, and peptide formation. Because direct de novo abiotic histidine synthesis is only strongly documented for the Shen-Or\u00f3 route, several pathways are explicitly salvage or convergence routes that funnel through the same proximal intermediate pool and are marked as speculative where required by the literature constraints.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": 