r than a single mandatory source."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Surface photochemical generation and concentration of hydrogen cyanide", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide mineral photoredox surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated evaporitic or volcanic surface setting; atmospheric discharge-derived nitrile chemistry concentrated in pools"}, "mechanism": "Photoredox and nitrile-forming atmospheric/surface chemistry generates HCN, which is trapped and concentrated in shallow pools.", "reasoning": "The report identifies HCN as the primary carbon and nitrogen source in both cyanosulfidic and purine-linked networks and notes atmospheric discharge plus UV-driven surface chemistry as critical feedstock generators (Miller, 1953; Patel et al., 2015; Ferris & Orgel, 1966). Exact direct conversion from formate/ammonia is a network-bridging abstraction of documented HCN-generating prebiotic contexts."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Formamidine formation from HCN and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite with UV-active mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated aqueous pools; transient accumulation limited by hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "HCN and NH3 undergo addition/rearrangement to amidine functionality under concentrated, mildly evaporative conditions.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly identifies formamidine as the key nitrogen-rich reagent formed from HCN and NH3, but emphasizes that its hydrolytic instability is a major bottleneck; mineral concentration is included to address this gap plausibly (Shen et al., 1990; Or\u00f3 & Shen, 1969)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Cyanamide formation from HCN-derived nitrile chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-photocatalytic mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed cyanosulfidic setting"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical nitrile transformations furnish cyanamide as a reactive condensed nitrile/amidine equivalent.", "reasoning": "Cyanamide is highlighted in the report as a versatile prebiotic reagent and direct precursor in 2-aminoimidazole synthesis. This step is included as a necessary network connection from the common HCN pool and is chemically consistent with prebiotic nitrile chemistry, though the exact route is less specifically detailed in the report (Sutherland, 2016; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Formose-derived conversion of glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde and erythrose", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals with clay concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pools; wet-dry concentration; borate stabilization of higher sugars"}, "mechanism": "Aldol/formose chemistry homologates glycolaldehyde to triose and tetrose products, with borate selectively stabilizing useful sugar isomers including erythrose.", "reasoning": "The report identifies erythrose as the key tetrose precursor in the Shen-Or\u00f3 route and glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde as central small sugars in systems chemistry; borate-stabilized formose chemistry is the standard prebiotic route connecting them (Benner et al., 2012; Ricardo et al., 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Shen-Or\u00f3 condensation of erythrose with formamidine to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration by clay and borate-stabilized sugar pools", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated aqueous environment; one-pot precursor mixture; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Condensation of the tetrose with formamidine gives an aminoaldose/amino-ketose manifold followed by Amadori-type rearrangement and cyclization to the imidazole aldehyde.", "reasoning": "This is the central literature-supported proximal histidine route: erythrose + formamidine yields imidazole-4-acetaldehyde via an Amadori-type rearrangement/cyclization under prebiotically plausible aqueous conditions (Shen, Or\u00f3, & Miller, 1987; Shen et al., 1990)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Strecker conversion of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde to histidine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay concentration with phosphate-buffered aqueous medium", "aqueous": "true", "other": "classical Strecker conditions in the same reaction mixture; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Aldehyde imination with ammonia followed by cyanide addition gives the alpha-aminonitrile precursor to histidine.", "reasoning": "The deep research explicitly states that imidazole-4-acetaldehyde is converted to histidine through classical Strecker synthesis, first forming the alpha-aminonitrile and then hydrolyzing to the amino acid (Shen, Or\u00f3, & Miller, 1987; Miller, 1957)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Hydrolysis of histidine aminonitrile to histidine", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditio