gues for molecular convergence between histidine and purine chemistry through shared imidazole intermediates, but does not provide a single experimentally established abiotic conversion from 2-aminoimidazole or AIC/AICAR to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde. This node-connecting salvage reaction is therefore explicitly speculative, added only to integrate the literature-supported imidazole pools into a complete network (Shen et al., 1990; Patel et al., 2015; White, 1976)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Cyanamide-mediated condensation of histidine to histidyl-histidine", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "cyanamide", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated pools or wet-dry cycling"}, "mechanism": "Cyanamide activates carboxylate function, enabling peptide bond formation between two histidine monomers.", "reasoning": "The report states that histidyl-histidine dipeptides have been synthesized in notable yield using cyanamide and that such peptides show catalytic behavior, supporting a downstream biochemical role for prebiotically formed histidine (Rode, 1999; the deep research summary on cyanamide-mediated His-His formation)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical Shen-Or\u00f3 route from erythrose", "description": "Surface tetrose erythrose condenses with formamidine to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde, then undergoes Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis to histidine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal-to-surface Shen-Or\u00f3 route via vent-derived glycolaldehyde", "description": "Hydrothermal reduction produces glycolaldehyde, which is converted on the surface into erythrose and then follows the Shen-Or\u00f3 sequence to histidine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_00