n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic alkaline vent conditions; H2-rich serpentinization setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 to one-carbon reduced carbon species.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fe-S minerals are central to hydrothermal carbon fixation scenarios and plausibly generate formate from CO2 and H2 under alkaline vent conditions, providing reduced C1 feedstock for downstream surface chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Roldan et al., 2015). This is literature-aligned as upstream feedstock generation, not a direct histidine-forming step.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde formation from reduced C1 carbon\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic Fischer-Tropsch-type and CO2 hydrogenation regime\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Further reduction of C1 carbon on iron-bearing mineral surfaces yields aldehydic products including formaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Magnetite- and iron-mediated hydrothermal reduction networks are widely invoked for generation of simple aldehydes and alcohols from reduced carbon inputs; here formaldehyde is included as a geochemically plausible precursor to surface sugar chemistry (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; He et al., 2010). Because selective formaldehyde accumulation is uncertain, this step should be considered plausible feedstock generation rather than directly demonstrated in the histidine literature.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal C-C coupling to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-470K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor hydrothermal setting with reduced iron-sulfur surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface-promoted carbonyl coupling of formaldehyde equivalents generates C2 hydroxyaldehydes.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step provides a network bridge from hydrothermal reduced carbon to the glycolaldehyde used in cyanosulfidic and sugar-forming chemistry. The report emphasizes glycolaldehyde as a key Sutherland-network feedstock, while hydrothermal generation is more speculative than surface atmospheric sourcing; therefore this reaction is explicitly treated as a cautious connector (Powner et al., 2009; Patel et al., 2015; speculative bridge noted).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent analog; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-catalyzed CO2 reduction and carbon fixation generate alpha-keto acids including pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied framework explicitly identifies pyruvate synthesis on greigite/magnetite as a hydrothermal reaction class. In this network pyruvate is not a direct histidine precursor but helps connect hydrothermal metabolic-style chemistry to broader prebiotic carbon flow (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN generation by atmospheric discharge and volcanic photochemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals as photochemical/mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"volcanic cloud or subaerial photochemical setting; UV irradiation and electrical discharge implied\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"High-energy atmospheric chemistry generates HCN and formaldehyde feedstocks, which are trapped into surface pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This corrects the previously criticized unsupported sourcing of HCN from formate plus ammonia. The supplied report explicitly identifies atmospheric discharge in volcanic ash-gas clouds and lightning as plausible feedstock sources of HCN and aldehydes on early Earth (Miller, 1953; Cleaves et al., 2008; as summarized in the research findings). Mineral surfaces here serve as required surface agents for adsorption, photochemistry, and concentration.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface conversion of HCN and ammonia to formamidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite/phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated shallow pool; anoxic; limited water activity favored because formamidine is hydrolytically labile\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide-derived amidine formation via reaction of HCN equivalents with ammonia in concentrated solution.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report explicitly states that formamidine can be formed from HCN and NH3 and is the indispensable amidine reagent in the Shen-Or\u00f3 route, while also emphasizing its instability. This reaction is therefore included as a bottleneck feedstock-generation step and marked as concentration-sensitive rather than robust (Shen, Or\u00f3 & Miller, 1987; as summarized in the report).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic production of cyanamide from HCN pools\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals/TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-driven cyanosulfidic setting with photoredox cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemically sustained cyanide chemistry yields activated nitrile/amidine-family reagents including cyanamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies cyanamide as a versatile prebiotic reagent in imidazole and peptide chemistry and places it within cyanosulfidic systems chemistry using HCN, H2S, and UV. Exact single-step geochemical conversion remains network-level rather than uniquely defined, so this reaction is a justified connector within the Sutherland-style framework (Sutherland, 2016; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface formose sequence from formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, and erythrose\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate/phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool or hot-spring wet-dry cycling; borate stabilization of sugars\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol/formose chemistry extends C1/C2 aldehydes to triose and tetrose sugars, with borate stabilizing otherwise labile products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research report identifies erythrose as the critical sugar precursor in the Shen-Or\u00f3 pathway and notes its origin in formose chemistry, despite low abundance and instability. Borate-mediated sugar stabilization is explicitly compatible with the supplied framework (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012; as contextual support for erythrose availability).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface phosphate-buffered cyclization of glycolaldehyde and cyanamide to 2-aminoimidazole\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"acidic pH approximately 5-7; high ammonium concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Phosphate-buffered condensation and cyclization form the aminoimidazole heterocycle from simple sugar and nitrogen feedstocks.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is directly grounded in the reported Sutherland-network result that 2-aminoimidazole forms from glycolaldehyde and cyanamide in the presence of inorganic phosphate and ammonium, with significant selectivity under mildly acidic conditions (Sutherland group; Fialho et al., 2018 as summarized in the report). It is included as an imidazole-pool convergence branch, not as a demonstrated conversion to histidine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN oligomerization to adenine and AIC-containing imidazole pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed concentrated cyanide solution; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN oligomerization and rearrangement generate purine-related imidazole heterocycles including adenine and AIC-like intermediates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly notes abiotic synthesis of adenine from HCN and NH3 and states that AIC/AICAR-related compounds can arise from HCN/NH3 chemistry. This reaction is used to represent the purine-linked heterocycle pool without asserting unsupported salvage into the Shen-Or\u00f3 intermediate, directly addressing prior feedback (Or\u00f3, 1961; Ferris et al., 1978; as summarized in the report).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Shen-Or\u00f3 condensation of erythrose and formamidine to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate-assisted sugar stabilization on clay-rich evaporitic surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated aqueous pool; one-pot pre-Strecker stage; Amadori-type rearrangement\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation of erythrose with formamidine produces an aminoaldose/aminoketose manifold that cyclizes through an Amadori-type rearrangement to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the best-supported prebiotic ring-construction step for histidine, explicitly described in the report as the first stage of the Shen-Or\u00f3-Miller synthesis. It constructs the histidine imidazole side chain from erythrose and formamidine (Shen, Or\u00f3 & Miller, 1987).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker conversion of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde to histidine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite/phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"classical Strecker setting in concentrated aqueous solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldehyde imine formation with ammonia followed by cyanide addition produces the alpha-aminonitrile precursor of histidine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly states that imidazole-4-acetaldehyde is transformed into an alpha-aminonitrile by direct addition of HCN and NH3 in the Shen-Or\u00f3 one-pot synthesis. Clay-catalyzed Strecker concentration is also consistent with the supplied framework (Shen, Or\u00f3 & Miller, 1987; Miller, 1953; Bada, 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic hydrolysis of histidine aminonitrile to histidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis in prebiotic pools during geothermal cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise nitrile hydration and hydrolysis convert the aminonitrile into the amino acid carboxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of alpha-aminonitriles to amino acids is the established terminal step of Strecker chemistry and is explicitly invoked in the Shen-Or\u00f3 histidine synthesis. This completes the only direct experimentally demonstrated route to histidine in the supplied literature (Shen, Or\u00f3 & Miller, 1987; Strecker, foundational chemistry).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic cyanamide-mediated condensation of histidine to histidyl-histidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated solution or wet-dry cycling; cyanamide as condensing agent\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanamide activates carboxyl groups for peptide bond formation, enabling histidine oligomerization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report notes that histidyl-histidine dipeptides have been synthesized prebiotically in appreciable yield using cyanamide and that such peptides may possess catalytic utility. This step shows biochemical elaboration after monomer formation (Rode and co-workers; as summarized in the report).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical Shen-Or\u00f3 histidine pathway from atmospheric HCN feedstock\",\n      \"description\": \"Atmospheric discharge supplies HCN and formaldehyde; HCN with ammonia gives formamidine; formose chemistry gives erythrose; erythrose plus formamidine gives imidazole-4-acetaldehyde; Strecker chemistry and hydrolysis yield histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-formate assisted sugar route into Shen-Or\u00f3 core\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduction makes formate, then formaldehyde; surface sugar chemistry produces erythrose; parallel atmospheric HCN gives formamidine; the validated Shen-Or\u00f3 core then yields histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal glycolaldehyde bridge into erythrose then histidine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbonyl coupling furnishes glycolaldehyde, which enters surface formose chemistry to produce erythrose; atmospheric HCN and ammonia generate formamidine; the Shen-Or\u00f3 and Strecker sequence gives histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface-only discharge plus formose route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface atmospheric photochemistry supplies both HCN and formaldehyde; formaldehyde enters formose chemistry to erythrose; HCN plus ammonia yields formamidine; the direct Shen-Or\u00f3 route gives histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Borate-stabilized erythrose pathway with hydrothermal carbon input\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde are concentrated in borate-bearing surface pools where erythrose is stabilized; independent HCN-derived formamidine enables imidazole-4-acetaldehyde formation and then histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-rich concentrated pool pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"In concentrated evaporitic pools, atmospheric HCN accumulates, producing formamidine efficiently enough to feed the erythrose-to-imidazole-4-acetaldehyde step, followed by Strecker histidine synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic imidazole-pool convergence supporting Shen-Or\u00f3 histidine formation\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN-rich surface chemistry branches to cyanamide and 2-aminoimidazole while simultaneously providing formamidine and erythrose for the validated histidine route. This pathway represents systems-chemistry coexistence rather than direct conversion of 2-aminoimidazole to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Purine-linked heterocycle coexistence pathway into direct Shen-Or\u00f3 core\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN oligomerization generates adenine and AIC-like compounds in the same cyanide pool that also supplies formamidine for the direct histidine pathway. This pathway emphasizes molecular convergence of purine and histidine imidazole chemistry without unsupported salvage interconversion.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-surface-biochemical fully connected pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction generates reduced carbon feedstocks, surface atmospheric chemistry generates HCN, surface wet-dry chemistry builds erythrose and the imidazole aldehyde, and biochemical pool hydrolysis yields histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Histidine-to-histidyl-histidine elaboration pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"The validated Shen-Or\u00f3 route yields histidine, which is then further condensed with cyanamide in prebiotic pools to form a catalytic dipeptide, illustrating downstream functional elaboration.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Histidine", "overall_strategy": "This network centers the literature-supported Shen-Or\u00f3-Miller route to histidine as the only direct, experimentally demonstrated histidine-forming pathway: erythrose + formamidine gives imidazole-4-acetaldehyde, which undergoes Strecker synthesis to histidine aminonitrile and hydrolysis to histidine. To satisfy the requested ten pathways while remaining faithful to the literature, the network explicitly treats multiple routes as convergent feedstock pathways into the same validated core rather than inventing unsupported direct salvage chemistry from other imidazole pools. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced carbon feedstocks such as formate, formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and pyruvate; surface chemistry supplies HCN, cyanamide/formamidine precursors, sugars, and imidazole-related heterocycles under UV, borate, phosphate, sulfide, TiO2, and clay influence; biochemical/prebiotic stages complete hydrolysis to histidine and optional peptide formation. The network therefore models environmental interconnection Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical, while distinguishing validated direct histidine synthesis from broader heterocycle-pool convergence hypotheses discussed in the literature.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C4H8O4", "iupac_name": "2,3,4-trihydroxybutanal", "common_name": "erythrose", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8O4/c5-1-3(7)4(8)2-6/h1,3-4,6-8H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "H3N", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "CH4N2", "iupac_name": "methanimidamide", "common_name": "formamidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4N2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H3,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "CH2N2", "iupac_name": "cyanamide", "common_name": "cyanamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2N2/c2-1-3/h(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H6N2O", "iupac_name": "2-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)ethanal", "common_name": "imidazole-4-acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6N2O/c8-2-1-5-3-6-4-7-5/h2-4H,1H2,(H,6,7)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C6H7N3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-1H-imidazole", "common_name": "2-aminoimidazole", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H5N3/c4-3-5-1-2-6-3/h1-2H,(H3,4,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H5N3O", "iupac_name": "5-amino-1H-imidazole-4-carboxamide", "common_name": "AIC", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H5N3O/c5-3-2(4(6)8)1-7-3/h1H,(H2,5,7)(H2,6,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H5N5", "iupac_name": "9H-purin-6-amine", "common_name": "adenine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H5N5/c6-5-4-7-2-8-1-3(4)9-5/h1-2H,(H2,6,7,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C6H8N4", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanenitrile", "common_name": "histidine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H8N4/c7-1-5(6(8)9)2-4-3-10-6/h3,5H,2H2,(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C6H9N3O2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanoic acid", "common_name": "histidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H9N3O2/c7-5(6(10)11)1-4-2-8-3-9-4/h2-3,5H,1,7H2,(H,10,11)(H,8,9)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C12H16N6O3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)-N-[1-amino-1-oxo-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propan-2-yl]propanamide", "common_name": "histidyl-histidine", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic alkaline vent conditions; H2-rich serpentinization setting"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 to one-carbon reduced carbon species.", "reasoning": "Fe-S minerals are central to hydrothermal carbon fixation scenarios and plausibly generate formate from CO2 and H2 under alkaline vent conditions, providing reduced C1 feedstock for downstream surface chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Roldan et al., 2015). This is literature-aligned as upstream feedstock generation, not a direct histidine-forming step."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal formaldehyde formation from reduced C1 carbon", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic Fischer-Tropsch-type and CO2 hydrogenation regime"}, "mechanism": "Further reduction of C1 carbon on iron-bearing mineral surfaces yields aldehydic products including formaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Magnetite- and iron-mediated hydrothermal reduction networks are widely invoked for generation of simple aldehydes and alcohols from reduced carbon inputs; here formaldehyde is included as a geochemically plausible precursor to surface sugar chemistry (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; He et al., 2010). Because selective formaldehyde accumulation is uncertain, this step should be considered plausible feedstock generation rather than directly demonstrated in the histidine literature."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal C-C coupling to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-470K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor hydrothermal setting with reduced iron-sulfur surfaces"}, "mechanism": "Surface-promoted carbonyl coupling of formaldehyde equivalents generates C2 hydroxyaldehydes.", "reasoning": "This step provides a network bridge from hydrothermal reduced carbon to the glycolaldehyde used in cyanosulfidic and sugar-forming chemistry. The report emphasizes glycolaldehyde as a key Sutherland-network feedstock, while hydrothermal generation is more speculative than surface atmospheric sourcing; therefore this reaction is explicitly treated as a cautious connector (Powner et al., 2009; Patel et al., 2015; speculative bridge noted)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent analog; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-catalyzed CO2 reduction and carbon fixation generate alpha-keto acids including pyruvate.", "reasoning": "The supplied framework explicitly identifies pyruvate synthesis on greigite/magnetite as a hydrothermal reaction class. In this network pyruvate is not a direct histidine precursor but helps connect hydrothermal metabolic-style chemistry to broader prebiotic carbon flow (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface HCN generation by atmospheric discharge and volcanic photochemistry", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals as photochemical/mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "volcanic cloud or subaerial photochemical setting; UV irradiation and electrical discharge implied"}, "mechanism": "High-energy atmospheric chemistry generates HCN and formaldehyde feedstocks, which are trapped into surface pools.", "reasoning": "This corrects the previously criticized unsupported sourcing of HCN from formate plus ammonia. The supplied report explicitly identifies atmospheric discharge in volcanic ash-gas clouds and lightning as plausible feedstock sources of HCN and aldehydes on early Earth (Miller, 1953; Cleaves et al., 2008; as summarized in the research findings). Mineral surfaces here serve as required surface agents for adsorption, photochemistry, and concentration."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface conversion of HCN and ammonia to formamidine", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite/phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated shallow pool; anoxic; limited water activity favored because formamidine is hydrolytically labile"}, "mechanism": "Cyanide-derived amidine formation via reaction of HCN equivalents with ammonia in concentrated solution.", "reasoning": "The research report explicitly states that formamidine can be formed from HCN and NH3 and is the indispensable amidine reagent in the Shen-Or\u00f3 route, while also emphasizing its instability. This reaction is therefore included as a bottleneck feedstock-generation step and marked as concentration-sensitive rather than robust (Shen, Or\u00f3 & Miller, 1987; as summarized in the report)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface cyanosulfidic production of cyanamide from HCN pools", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals/TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-driven cyanosulfidic setting with photoredox cycling"}, "mechanism": "Photochemically sustained cyanide chemistry yields activated nitrile/amidine-family reagents including cyanamide.", "reasoning": "The report identifies cyanamide as a versatile prebiotic reagent in imidazole and peptide chemistry and places it within cyanosulfidic systems chemistry using HCN, H2S, and UV. Exact single-step geochemical conversion remains network-level rather than uniquely defined, so this reaction is a justified connector within the Sutherland-style framework (Sutherland, 2016; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface formose sequence from formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, and erythrose", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate/phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool or hot-spring wet-dry cycling; borate stabilization of sugars"}, "mechanism": "Aldol/formose chemistry extends C1/C2 aldehydes to triose and tetrose sugars, with borate stabilizing otherwise labile products.", "reasoning": "The deep research report identifies erythrose as the critical sugar precursor in the Shen-Or\u00f3 pathway and notes its origin in formose chemistry, despite low abundance and instability. Borate-mediated sugar stabilization is explicitly compatible with the supplied framework (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012; as contextual support for erythrose availability)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Surface phosphate-buffered cyclization of glycolaldehyde and cyanamide to 2-aminoimidazole", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_011", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "acidic pH approximately 5-7; high ammonium concentration"}, "mechanism": "Phosphate-buffered condensation and cyclization form the aminoimidazole heterocycle from simple sugar and nitrogen feedstocks.", "reasoning": "This is directly grounded in the reported Sutherland-network result that 2-aminoimidazole forms from glycolaldehyde and cyanamide in the presence of inorganic phosphate and ammonium, with significant selectivity under mildly acidic conditions (Sutherland group; Fialho et al., 2018 as summarized in the report). It is included as an imidazole-pool convergence branch, not as a demonstrated conversion to histidine."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Surface HCN oligomerization to adenine and AIC-containing imidazole pool", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed concentrated cyanide solution; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "HCN oligomerization and rearrangement generate purine-related imidazole heterocycles including adenine and AIC-like intermediates.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly notes abiotic synthesis of adenine from HCN and NH3 and states that AIC/AICAR-related compounds can arise from HCN/NH3 chemistry. This reaction is used to represent the purine-linked heterocycle pool without asserting unsupported salvage into the Shen-Or\u00f3 intermediate, directly addressing prior feedback (Or\u00f3, 1961; Ferris et al., 1978; as summarized in the report)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Surface Shen-Or\u00f3 condensation of erythrose and formamidine to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate-assisted sugar stabilization on clay-rich evaporitic surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated aqueous pool; one-pot pre-Strecker stage; Amadori-type rearrangement"}, "mechanism": "Condensation of erythrose with formamidine produces an aminoaldose/aminoketose manifold that cyclizes through an Amadori-type rearrangement to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "This is the best-supported prebiotic ring-construction step for histidine, explicitly described in the report as the first stage of the Shen-Or\u00f3-Miller synthesis. It constructs the histidine imidazole side chain from erythrose and formamidine (Shen, Or\u00f3 & Miller, 1987)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Surface Strecker conversion of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde to histidine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_008", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite/phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "classical Strecker setting in concentrated aqueous solution"}, "mechanism": "Aldehyde imine formation with ammonia followed by cyanide addition produces the alpha-aminonitrile precursor of histidine.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly states that imidazole-4-acetaldehyde is transformed into an alpha-aminonitrile by direct addition of HCN and NH3 in the Shen-Or\u00f3 one-pot synthesis. Clay-catalyzed Strecker concentration is also consistent with the supplied framework (Shen, Or\u00f3 & Miller, 1987; Miller, 1953; Bada, 2013)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Biochemical/prebiotic hydrolysis of histidine aminonitrile to histidine", "inputs": ["mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous hydrolysis in prebiotic pools during geothermal cycling"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise nitrile hydration and hydrolysis convert the aminonitrile into the amino acid carboxylate.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of alpha-aminonitriles to amino acids is the established terminal step of Strecker chemistry and is explicitly invoked in the Shen-Or\u00f3 histidine synthesis. This completes the only direct experimentally demonstrated route to histidine in the supplied literature (Shen, Or\u00f3 & Miller, 1987; Strecker, foundational chemistry)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Biochemical/prebiotic cyanamide-mediated condensation of histidine to histidyl-histidine", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated solution or wet-dry cycling; cyanamide as condensing agent"}, "mechanism": "Cyanamide activates carboxyl groups for peptide bond formation, enabling histidine oligomerization.", "reasoning": "The report notes that histidyl-histidine dipeptides have been synthesized prebiotically in appreciable yield using cyanamide and that such peptides may possess catalytic utility. This step shows biochemical elaboration after monomer formation (Rode and co-workers; as summarized in the report)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical Shen-Or\u00f3 histidine pathway from atmospheric HCN feedstock", "description": "Atmospheric discharge supplies HCN and formaldehyde; HCN with ammonia gives formamidine; formose chemistry gives erythrose; erythrose plus formamidine gives imidazole-4-acetaldehyde; Strecker chemistry and hydrolysis yield histidine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_007", "mol_012", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal-formate assisted sugar route into Shen-Or\u00f3 core", "description": "Hydrothermal reduction makes formate, then formaldehyde; surface sugar chemistry produces erythrose; parallel atmospheric HCN gives formamidine; the validated Shen-Or\u00f3 core then yields histidine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_010", "mol_007", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal glycolaldehyde bridge into erythrose then histidine", "description": "Hydrothermal carbonyl coupling furnishes glycolaldehyde, which enters surface formose chemistry to produce erythrose; atmospheric HCN and ammonia generate formamidine; the Shen-Or\u00f3 and St