tion addresses a known literature challenge around sugar survival and selection. The pathway is still limited by speculative formamidine supply and the modest support for hydrothermal formaldehyde generation, but overall it is plausible and well integrated.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_002", "rxn_006"], "suggestions": ["State borate explicitly in the operative reaction details rather than only in pathway labeling.", "Separate sugar stabilization from sugar generation to avoid overstating selectivity.", "Ground formamidine production in a more explicit prebiotic concentration scenario."]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_005": 0.78, "rxn_006": 0.62, "rxn_011": 0.94, "rxn_012": 0.95, "rxn_013": 0.92, "rxn_008": 0.7}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.8, "pathway_coherence": 0.87, "environmental_progression": 0.85, "target_achievement": 0.96, "overall_confidence": 0.85, "feedback": "This pathway appropriately leverages HCN-rich pools, which are literature-consistent for feedstock accumulation and Strecker chemistry. However, high HCN alone does not solve the major bottlenecks of erythrose selectivity and formamidine instability. Still, the direct histidine-forming segment remains strong.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_008"], "suggestions": ["Clarify whether HCN concentration is achieved by evaporation, freezing, or recurrent input.", "Discuss side-reaction competition in concentrated HCN systems.", "Keep the Shen-Or\u00f3 core distinct from broader HCN chemistry to preserve literature fidelity."]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_005": 0.78, "rxn_007": 0.74, "rxn_009": 0.9, "rxn_006": 0.62, "rxn_008": 0.7, "rxn_011": 0.94, "rxn_012": 0.95, "rxn_013": 0.92}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.79, "pathway_coherence": 0.8, "environmental_progression": 0.88, "target_achievement": 0.95, "overall_confidence": 0.81, "feedback": "This pathway is chemically richer and aligns with the literature view that cyanosulf